Here's the xUnit equivalent:

```csharp
// xUnit uses IClassFixture<T> for one-time setup/teardown
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();  // OneTimeSetUp
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();     // OneTimeTearDown
    }
}

// xUnit uses constructor/Dispose for per-test setup/teardown
public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        // SetUp → constructor
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        // TearDown → Dispose
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

**Key mappings:**

| NUnit | xUnit |
|-------|-------|
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` | `IClassFixture<T>` constructor |
| `[OneTimeTearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>.Dispose()` |
| `[SetUp]` | Test class constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | Test class `IDisposable.Dispose()` |
| `[TestFixture]` | *(removed — not needed)* |
| `[Test]` | `[Fact]` |

xUnit creates a **new instance** of the test class per test, so the constructor/Dispose naturally gives you per-test setup/teardown. The shared fixture is injected via `IClassFixture<T>` and lives for the lifetime of the class.
